ABSTRACT
Background and objective: This meta-analysis was performed to evaluate the effect and safety of selexipag in the
treatment of pulmonary hypertension and to explore the effect of selexipag on cardiac function indexes in PAH
patients.
Methods: Electronic databases, including the Cochrane Library, EMBASE, and PubMed databases, were searched.
Endnote software X9 was used for study selection, and the Cochrane Risk of Bias Tool was used for literature
screening and quality assessment. Data analysis was performed using RevMan 5.3 software, and GRADE was used
to assess the evidence level.
Results: Ten studies were nally selected in accordance with the standard. A total of 10 papers were included. A
total of 1322 patients were included, including 723 in the trial group and 599 in the control group. Patients with
PAH treated with selexipag were included in the trial group, and patients with PAH treated with placebo were
included in the control group. The results of the study showed that selexipag was effective in reducing mortality
in patients (WMD=0.70, 95% CI: 0.530.94, P = 0.02). Selexipag effectively increased the 6-min walk distance
(WMD=33.79, 95% CI: 2.6964.90, P=0.03). Selexipag also effectively increased the 6-min distance between
baseline and follow-up (WMD = 15.28, 95% CI: 7.7622.80, P < 0.0001). Selexipag effectively reduced PVR
(WMD = 230.96, 95% CI: 445.94 to 15.97, P = 0.04). Selexipag signicantly reduced PVR between baseline
and follow-up (WMD = 139.62, 95% CI: 215.32 to 63.91, P = 0.0003). The adverse reactions of selexipag
were mild with headache, diarrhea and nausea reported as the main symptoms.
Conclusion: Selexipag is a new drug with mild adverse reactions and is safe for the treatment of PAH. This drug
signicantly prolongs the level of 6MWD in PAH patients, reduces the fatality rate, improves WHO FC and re-
duces PVR. The effects of this drug on CI, mPAP, MRAP, SvO
2
and other indicators still need to be further
conrmed.
Prospero registration: CRD42021245557.
1. Introduction
Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a disease mainly charac-
terized by abnormal pulmonary arterioles and elevated pulmonary
vascular resistance based on a variety of etiologies and pathogeneses.
Abnormalities in pulmonary arterioles include increased vasoconstric-
tion, vascular remodeling, smooth muscle cell proliferation and in situ
thrombosis. The pathogenesis of pulmonary arterial hypertension is
thought to be due to an imbalance in the quantity and proportion of
vasoactive substances (including prostacyclin, nitric oxide, and
endothelin-1) and abnormal contraction, proliferation, and migration of
vascular smooth muscle cells. The continuous increase in pulmonary
pressure leads to an increase in the right ventricular back load, leading
to right heart failure. In the late stage, most patients with pulmonary
hypertension die due to uncontrollable right heart failure. Although

progress has been made in modern treatments, the morbidity and mor-
tality rates remain high. Data show that 15 out of every 1 million people
suffer from PAH [1]. There are three main molecular pathways for
PAH-targeted therapy in the clinic, including nitric oxide cyclic gua-
nosine monophosphatase, the endothelin receptor and the prostacyclin
receptor. The prostacyclin receptor (IP) is a membrane receptor coupled
with a GS-type protein that leads to an increase in cAMP and results in
vasodilation. IP can also conjugate with GI and GQ proteins, resulting in
reduced contraction, proliferation and migration of vascular smooth
muscle cells. Therefore, enhancing the activation of the prostacyclin
pathway is one of the main strategies for the treatment of pulmonary
arterial hypertension [2]. Selexipag is an oral, highly selective prosta-
cyclin (IP) receptor agonist that was approved by the Food and Drug
Administration in December 2015 for the treatment of World Health
Organization (WHO) Group 1 functional II or III patients to slow disease
progression and reduce mortality [1]. Selexipag has a similar mecha-
nism to prostacyclin (PGI2) but is a nonprostaglandin-like IP receptor
agonist. After oral administration, selexipag is rapidly absorbed and
then hydrolyzed by the liver to its more active metabolite, which is
approximately 37-fold more potent as the original metabolite in acti-
vating the IP receptor [2]. At present, a systematic evaluation on the
efcacy and safety of selexipag in the treatment of patients with PAH is
lacking. Based on the data extracted from relevant literature retrieved
from the PubMed database, EMBASE database and Cochrane Library
database, this study conducted a meta-analysis on the efcacy and safety
of selexipag in the treatment of PAH patients.
2. Materials and methods
2.1. Literature inclusion and exclusion criteria
2.1.1. Inclusion criteria
(1) Type of literature: full-text published literature to study the
therapeutic effect of selexipag on patients with pulmonary arte-
rial hypertension (PAH) through randomized controlled studies
and observational studies;
(2) The establishment time of the selected literature: October 2020;
(3) Research object: adult patients with pulmonary hypertension
(PAH) or any recognized diagnostic criteria, no selexipag was
taken before the study, regular medication and timely follow-up
were conducted after the study;
(4) Intervention: the experimental group was treated with selexipag
under the same conditions as the control group, or clinical data
obtained after selexipag treatment for pulmonary hypertension
were compared with baseline follow-up;
(5) Outcome measures: case fatality rate during treatment and
follow-up, incidence of worsening events in WHO functional
classication(WHO FC), incidence of improvement in WHO
functional classication(WHO FC), 6-min walk distance (6MWD),
pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR), cardiac index (CI), mean
pulmonary arterial pressure (mPAP), mean right atrial pressure
(mRAP), mixed venous oxygen saturation (SvO
2
), and common
adverse reactions.
2.1.2. Exclusion criteria
(1) The subjects of this study were not PAH patients, they took
selexipag before participating in the study, they used drugs
irregularly after the start of the study and were lost to follow-up;
(2) The literature includes reviews, case reports, pharmacological
studies and animal studies
(3) Repetition of the published articles;
(4) The literature provides partial missing data or data from which
outcome indicators cannot be extracted
(5) The full text of the literature cannot be consulted.
2.2. Literature retrieval strategy
PubMed, EMBASE and Cochrane Library databases were searched to
select the literature from the date of establishment to October 2020. The
search terms included free words and MeSH subject words. The English
literature can be retrieved with the key words selexipag, uptravi,
NS-304, ACT 293987, ACT293987, ACT-293987, Arterial Hy-
pertension, Pulmonary, hypertension, Pulmonary Arterial,
treatment, treatments, therapy, therapeutic and therapies. In
total, 43 English literature were identied. Fig. 1 shows the detailed
literature screening process.
2.3. Literature screening and data extraction
After the literature was screened from the database, Endnote was
used to manage the screened literature, and duplicate studies were
excluded using the software. Two researchers then screened the studies
separately. In the initial screening, irrelevant articles were excluded
according to the standard by reading the titles and abstracts of each
article. During the second screening, the full text of articles were
reviewed, and articles for which the outcome data could not be extracted
were excluded. After the second screening, the relevant data of the
included literature were extracted. Data extracted included the rst
author, year of publication, study population, race, age, sample size,
research method, main outcome, follow-up time and adverse reactions.
2.4. Literature quality assessment
The Cochrane Bias Risk Assessment Table and Newcastle-Ottawa
Scale were used by two researchers as bias risk assessment tools in
this study to evaluate the quality of the literature. When opinions differ,
the decision is reached through discussion or based on the third in-
vestigators intervention. The evaluation indicates that the study by
Adaani Frost exhibits high-risk selection bias, implementation bias, and
measurement bias. Nobuhiro has high-risk implementation bias, mea-
surement bias, and other biases, and Sean has other high-risk biases. In
addition, there were four studies with an unclear risk of selection bias
due to insufcient descriptions of details. In addition, the risk of
implementation bias and measurement bias is unknown in the studies by
Charlotte and Gerald.
Given that only 5 of the included studies are randomized controlled
trials, we used the Cochrane Bias Risk Assessment to evaluate random-
ized controlled trials and the NOS scale to evaluate retrospective
experiments.
According to the Cochrane Bias Risk Assessment Table, for studies
that basically met these criteria, the probability of various biases was
small, and the quality grade was A. If the study partially met these
criteria, the probability of bias was moderate, and the quality grade was
B. If the study did not meet these criteria at all, the probability of bias
was high, and the quality grade was C. Among the 5 included RCTs, 3
were grade A, and 2 were grade B.

2.5. Statistical analysis
For the included literature, all statistical analyses were performed
using RevMan version 5.3 provided by the Cochrane Collaboration for
meta-analysis of the data. For binary variables, including the clinical
event improvement rate or worsening rate, case fatality rate, and
adverse reaction rate, the odds ratio (OR) was used as the effect index.
Continuous variables were assessed using the weighted mean difference
(WMD), and the condence interval was 95%. (95% CI). Literature
heterogeneity was assessed based on I
2
. If the included literature had no
statistical heterogeneity (P > 0.01, I
2
< 50%), the study was assessed
using a xed-effect model. If the included study was statistically het-
erogeneous (P < 0.01, I
2
> 50%), the study was assessed using a
random-effects model. In addition, sensitivity analysis or subgroup
analysis was performed to understand the source of heterogeneity. If the
data were reported as the median (or extreme values), they were con-
verted into the standard deviation. Then, then meta-analysis was per-
formed [5].
3. Results
3.1. Basic information of included literature
Ten studies [615] were included in this study, including 5 ran-
domized controlled trials, 2 prospective studies and 3 observational
studies published from 2012 to 2020. The basic characteristics of the
included studies are shown in Table 1.
3.2. Effect of intervention
Five randomized controlled trials were included in the literature,
including the studies by Olivier Sitbon [12], Gerald Simonneau [11],
Nobuhiro Tanabe [13], Maurice Beghetti [7], and Sean Gaine [10]. The
studies of Olivier Sitbon, Sean Gaine and Maurice Beghetti focus on the
GRIPHON method. The GRIPHON study is a multicenter, double-blind,
randomized, parallel group, placebo-controlled, event-driven, phase III
trial. After standard screening, patients were randomly assigned to
receive placebo or selexipag at a ratio of 1:1. During the dose adjustment
phase, the selexipag group started with two doses of 200
g daily, and
the doses were increased by 200
g twice a week until patients devel-
oped hard-to-control adverse effects, such as headache or jaw pain. The

placebo group at a ratio of 3:1, which differed from the intervention

TRANSIT-1, a prospective, multicenter, open-label, single-group, phase
3B trial. Nobuhiro Tanabes prospective study was a multicenter,
open-label, noncomparative phase II trial. In 2 prospective studies and 3

protocol was used as the standard [6,8,9,14,15].

4. Discussion
Pulmonary arterial hypertension is a life-threatening form of pul-
monary vascular disease with a median survival of 57 years after
diagnosis [3]. At present, there are three main pathways for targeted
therapy of PAH patients: nitric oxide, endothelin and prostacyclin.
Prostacyclin, also known as prostaglandin I
2
, is a derivative of arach-
idonic acid produced primarily by vascular endothelial cells. Prostacy-
clin mainly acts through G protein-coupled IP receptors, leading to an
increase in cyclic adenosine monophosphate. The effects of prostacyclin
on IP receptors include vasodilation, especially in the presence of
increased pulmonary vascular tone; inhibition of vascular smooth
muscle cell proliferation; and platelet aggregation. The main patholog-
ical change of pulmonary arterial hypertension is abnormal contraction
of small pulmonary vessels, so the study of the prostacyclin pathway is
particularly important. However, the limitations of the half-life and
bioavailability of oral prostaglandins have led to a wider study of
compounds with IP receptor activity [4]. The synthesis of selexipag,
which was rst reported in 2007, is structurally different from other
drugs targeting the PGI
2
pathway in that it is a nonprostaglandin IP
receptor agonist rather than a PGI
2
or PGI
2
analog. Its high selectivity for
human IP receptors makes it a promising and new therapeutic option in
PAH therapy [5]. Although selexipag is approved by the US Food and
Drug Administration (FDA) for the clinical treatment of patients, studies
on the efcacy and safety of selexipag are limited, and the results have
not been widely recognized. From the perspective of evidence-based
medicine, this paper analyzes the efcacy and tolerance of the drug
and provides a new research direction.
Because less than 10 studies were included in this meta-analysis, a
funnel plot study was not performed. At present, the 6-min walk distance
is more commonly used as an index to evaluate the motor ability of
patients with PAH [16]. The results of this study show that selexipag can
prolong the 6MWD of patients with PAH compared with placebo
WMD=33.79, 95% CI: 2.6964.90, P=0.03). Compared with baseline,
selexipag extends 6MWD in PAH patients after treatment(WMD = 15.28,
95% CI: 7.7622.80, P < 0.0001). Selexipag can signicantly improve
the exercise capacity of patients with PAH.
The etiology of PAH is complex, and the prognosis is poor. In the
included literature, the case fatality rate was used as the primary follow-
up endpoint. The results of this study showed that selexipag effectively
reduced the case fatality rate of patients compared with placebo
(WMD=0.70, 95% CI: 0.530.94, P=0.02). Although selexipag did not
show a signicant reduction in the incidence of WHO FC worsening
events (WMD = 0.79, 95% CI: 0.601.04, P = 0.09), treatment with
selexipag signicantly increased the incidence of WHO FC improvement
events (WMD = 1.59, 95% CI: 1.092.32, P = 0.02). The quality of the
evidence was rated as high. The included literature [1113] indicated
that the improvement of WHO FC mostly occurred in patients with WHO
FC III and IV, suggesting that selexipag may have a better curative effect
in the treatment of moderate and severe PAH patients, effectively delay
the progress of PAH, and even improve patient conditions.
Experts agree that pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a syn-
drome in which pulmonary vascular resistance is increased due to pul-
monary arterial blood ow limitation and eventually leads to right
ventricular failure. Pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR), cardiac index
(CI), mean pulmonary arterial pressure(mPAP), mean right atrial pres-
sure (mRAP), and mixed venous oxygen saturation (SvO
2
) were used to
evaluate the clinical efcacy of selexipag. The results of this study show
that compared with placebo, selexipag signicantly reduces PVR (WMD
= 230.96, 95% CI: 445.94 to 15.97, P = 0.04). Compared with the
baseline period, the results also indicate that selexipag effectively im-
proves the condition of elevated pulmonary vascular resistance.
Compared with placebo and baseline, the results consistently indicate
that selexipag effectively increases the cardiac index (CI). However, the
GRADE evidence quality assessment showed that the evidence for PVR
and CI was of medium to low quality. More studies and clinical data are
needed to further conrm whether selexipag effectively improves lung
function. Whether selexipag effectively alters mPAP, mRAP, SvO
2
and
other indicators remains unknown. N-terminal pro-B-type natriuretic
peptide (NT-proBNP) an indicator of cardiac function. Olivier Sitbon
[12] and Michaela Barnikel [6] report that selexipag effectively reduces
NT-proBNP, whereas data from Charlotte Berlier [8] and Adaani Frost,
MD [9] show that selexipag can only maintain NT-proBNP levels. It is
not believed that selexipag affects NT-proBNP. More studies and clinical
data are needed to conrm this notion.
All 10 included articles [615] reported numerous adverse reactions
during selexipag treatment. This study conducted a meta-analysis of
common headache, diarrhea, nausea, jaw pain, and myalgia. The results
showed signicant differences between the above adverse reactions and
placebo, but the results did not indicate that selexipag treatment in-
creases the incidence of adverse reactions (WMD=1.86, 95% CI:
0.933.73, P=0.08). Headache is the most common adverse reaction,
and most patients tolerate it. However, if these patients take medicine or
reduce the dosage, the symptoms will disappear.
Patients adherence to PAH drugs is high [22], and treatment ad-
justments are less common before using or switching to selexipag.
Pharmacy costs, which largely determine the average baseline health
care costs, increase substantially over time, but average health care costs
appear to decline with additional treatment or a switch to selexipag
[21], which suggests that clinical patients need to pay attention to the
acceptance of selexipag and adjust treatment strategies or upgrade
treatment before clinical deterioration occurs.
Selexipag has many advantages over traditional prostaglandin drugs
[17]. The John W. McConnell study showed that in the selexipag group,
the risk of all-cause hospitalization was reduced by 46%, and the risk of
hospitalization related to pulmonary hypertension was reduced by 47%.
In the oral treprostinil group, the all-cause hospitalization rate
decreased by 42%, and the hospitalization rate related to pulmonary
hypertension decreased by 46%. Compared with oral treprostinil,
selexipag has a lower hospitalization risk and hospitalization rate [26].
Traditional prostaglandin drug therapy includes intravenous infusion,
inhalation, and oral administration of treprostinil. Although various
studies have shown good therapeutic outcomes and prognosis for PAH
patients [1820,23], both intravenous infusion and inhalation routes
have their own limitations [23]. Local pain at the intravenous injection
site has been noted [20]. Although the oral route has no serious side
effects, the Tapson VF study showed that the primary endpoint of 6MWD
M. Chen et al.
Pulmonary Pharmacology & Therapeutics 72 (2022) 102100
9
improvement at week 16 did not meet the target [23], so the clinical
efcacy needs to be further studied. As an oral, highly selective pros-
tacyclin (IP) receptor agonist, selexipag [24] signicantly reduce the
mortality rate of PAH patients compared with placebo in a GRIPHON
study [12]. According to the 10 included studies, although the indi-
vidualized dose in the control group was chosen according to the actual
situation of the patients, the dose in the GRIPHON study served as a
standard [615]. The biggest advantage of selexipag is that it has a
half-life of 7.9 h and allows oral administration twice a day [11].
Selexipag was well tolerated at a dose of up to 800 mg [25]. Therefore,
the authors suggest that the dose in the GRIPHON study can be used as a
standard in the clinic, i.e., 200 mg twice a day and 200 mg per week for a
maximum tolerable dose of 1600 mg until uncontrollable side effects
occur. The daily dose is then reduced by 200 mg for a typical course of 3
months [615]. Due to severe adverse reactions to treprostinil, Frost As
Transit 1 study of the transition from inhaled treprostinil to oral selex-
ipag in patients with pulmonary arterial hypertension showed that the
transition from inhaled treprostinil to oral selexipag in PAH patients was
successful and well tolerated in most patients [9]. Therefore, the authors
suggest that selexipag can be used as a treatment alone or as a transi-
tional treatment with other drugs.
Limitations of this study: 1. Given that the number of studies on
selexipag are limited, the number of included studies and sample size of
this meta-analysis is small, which may impact the reliability of the re-
sults. The results indicate that selexipag treatment affects PVR, CI and
NT-proBNP. The impact of other indicators require further study. 2.
Numerous adverse reactions were reported in the included literature,
and only common adverse reactions were selected for analysis. Thus,
this study does not provide a comprehensive analysis. 3. Obvious het-
erogeneity in the results of 6WMD changes between the selexipag group
and placebo group was noted among the studies. Sensitivity analysis was
used. We found signicant heterogeneity between Maurice Beghetti and
Sean Gaine, and the clinical data of Maurice Beghetti and Sean Gaine
were signicantly different from Olivier Sitbon. This study avoided the
impact of duplicate data on the results. However, given the limitations of
the study, comprehensive clinical data of GRIPHON were not extracted
to group the race, the severity of PAH, etc. In addition, data for subgroup
analysis was lacking, and our analysis failed to understand the source of
heterogeneity, which may have an impact on the reliability of the re-
sults. Thus, the quality of evidence evaluation was reduced to medium
quality. 4. Most of the included literature collected follow-up outcome
indicators at approximately 26 weeks of treatment. Whether selexipag
has long-term curative effects on PAH cannot be assessed given the lack
of long-term follow-up data. 5. The basic diseases that cause PAH in the
included literature differ, and different basic diseases may have different
responses to the drugs. Among them, only Maurice Beghetti and Sean
Gaine treat congenital heart disease and perform pulmonary arterial
hypertension and connective tissue disease-related pulmonary arterial
hypertension analysis. Due to the limitations of the research data, this
study failed to conduct subgroup analysis based on the underlying dis-
eases. 6. This drug was taken orally, but intravenous infusion was per-
formed in the included literature. This study did not analyze the
inuence of oral administration and intravenous infusion on drug
efcacy.
5. Conclusion
In conclusion, as an oral and highly selective prostacyclin (IP) re-
ceptor agonist, selexipag has been gradually applied in the clinical
treatment of PAH patients, representing a new choice in PAH treatment.
This study indicate that selexipag reduces the mortality rate of PAH
patients, increases the 6MWD and CI levels of PAH patients, signicantly
reduces PVR, and simultaneously increases the WHO FC improvement in
event occurrence. Selexipag exhibits good curative effects in patients
with medium to severe disease, and patients generally do not exhibit
adverse reactions. However, selexipag did not provide benets in terms
of mPAP, mRAP, and SvO
2
. It remains uncertain whether selexipag has
an impact on NT-proBNP. In future studies, the effect of selexipag on
other cardiopulmonary function measures will need to be conrmed. In
addition, in the future, we should also focus on the long-term efcacy of
selexipag as well as the impact of dose concentration and medication on
drug efcacy and explore the value of clinical-economic-adverse re-
actions and the specic efcacy and safety of PAH patients with
different underlying diseases.
